{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "It represents words according to their frequency in the corpus, disregarding order and context.",
    "N-grams are extensions of BoW that breaks the corpus into a contiguous sequence of n words.",
    "It can capture more context around each word, but produces a sparser feature set than BoW.",
    "BoW and N-grams assume that words that occur more frequently are more relevant and do not always hold true.",
    "Term frequency-inverse document frequency (TF-IDF) (Salton et al. 1975) adds another metric of how rarely a word occurs across the entire corpus and assigns rarer words a higher score."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Term frequency-inverse document frequency (TF-IDF) (Salton et al. 1975) adds another metric of how rarely a word occurs across the entire corpus and assigns rarer words a higher score."
